window.GAME_DATA = {"//":"GENERATED from content/*.md by tools/build-content.mjs. Do not edit; edit the Markdown in content/ and run: npm run build","generatedAt":"2026-07-21T02:44:00.503Z","acts":[{"act":1,"label":"Act 1 · Solo Players","mode":"solo"},{"act":2,"label":"Act 2 · Team Discussion | Alternate","mode":"team-alternate"},{"act":3,"label":"Act 3 · Team Discussion | Simultaneous","mode":"team-simultaneous"}],"rows":[{"row":1,"act":1,"points":100,"time":"2:00","timeSeconds":120},{"row":2,"act":1,"points":200,"time":"2:00","timeSeconds":120},{"row":3,"act":2,"points":300,"time":"3:00","timeSeconds":180},{"row":4,"act":2,"points":400,"time":"3:00","timeSeconds":180},{"row":5,"act":3,"points":500,"time":"4:00","timeSeconds":240},{"row":6,"act":3,"points":600,"time":"4:00","timeSeconds":240}],"columns":[{"position":1,"id":"estimation","name":"Estimation","subheader":"reason under uncertainty","file":"estimation.md"},{"position":2,"id":"logic-paradox","name":"Logic / Paradox","subheader":"reason vs your own gut","file":"logic-paradox.md"},{"position":3,"id":"strategy","name":"Strategy","subheader":"reason about other minds","file":"strategy.md"},{"position":4,"id":"data-literacy","name":"Data Literacy","subheader":"interrogate a claim","file":"data-literacy.md"}],"questions":{"estimation":[{"row":1,"title":"Scaling a number you already know","question":"If you eat Brazilian food once a week, how many times is that in a year?","answer":"About 52 times. A year is roughly 52 weeks, so once a week is about 52.","scoringGate":"Any answer that shows how they got there. Landing near 52 with a method counts. A bare \"52\" with no explanation does not, the whole point of this row is showing a little reasoning.","path":"Two ways, both fine. Once a week times 52 weeks. Four weeks a month times 12 months is 48, then add 2 or 3 weeks because months run a little longer than four weeks. That small correction is a nice instinct to point out.","hints":"\"How many weeks are in a year?\" \"If you're not sure, try weeks in a month times months in a year.\"","whyThisLevel":"The easiest kind of estimation. Take a number you already roughly know and scale it up, one or two steps of multiplication. It is the warm-up: the goal is to show that estimating is doable, not to stump anyone."},{"row":2,"title":"Filling a space","question":"How many soccer balls fit in this room?","answer":"Depends on the room, so there is no single number. For a rough sense: a soccer ball is about 22 cm across, so along a 4-meter wall you would fit about 18, and you multiply that in three directions (across, deep, and up).","scoringGate":"A sensible method, not a specific number. Bonus recognition if they remember that round balls leave gaps and knock the total down a bit.","path":"Room volume divided by one ball's volume. Balls across, times balls deep, times layers stacked up.","hints":"\"About how big is a soccer ball? About how big is this room?\" \"Try how many fit along the floor, then how many layers up to the ceiling.\"","takeaway":"The gaps between round balls mean the real number is a bit lower than the tidy math.","whyThisLevel":"Still easy and still solo, but a different kind of thinking. Instead of scaling a number, you picture how objects fill a space. The skill is turning messy real things into simple shapes: a ball into a cube, the room into an empty box."},{"row":3,"title":"Guessing a share and building on it","question":"How many people in San Francisco go camping over a summer weekend?","answer":"No single right number, it depends on the share you assume. Rough sketch: SF has about 800,000 to 900,000 people; if you guess a small slice, say 1 to 3 percent, go camping on a given summer weekend, that is very roughly 10,000 to 25,000 people.","scoringGate":"A sensible set of steps and a defensible guess for the camping share. Two teams can pick different percentages and both earn full points if they can make a case.","path":"SF population times the guessed share who camp that weekend. The share is the hard part and the whole point of the discussion.","hints":"\"Start with how many people live in SF.\" \"What share of them do you think actually go camping on a summer weekend? There's no right answer, just make a case.\"","whyThisLevel":"The first real jump. Now one number in the chain is something nobody knows, what share of people actually go camping, and the group has to guess it and argue about it. This is where estimating becomes building a little model, which is why teams start working together here."},{"row":4,"title":"Splitting a total across what one unit handles","question":"A Waymo needs to be towed about 4 times a year. How many tow trucks does the Bay Area need to keep its Waymo fleet moving?","answer":"Depends on how many Waymos there are and how much a truck can do, so there is no fixed number. Sketch: a few thousand Waymos times 4 tows a year is tens of thousands of tows; one truck doing maybe 6 tows a day times about 250 workdays is roughly 1,500 a year; divide and you get a rough truck count.","scoringGate":"Building both estimates (total towing needed, and one truck's yearly capacity) and combining them by dividing. The division is the thing to look for. Their guess at fleet size does not need to be exact.","path":"Total towing needed = number of Waymos times 4 a year. One truck's capacity = tows per day times workdays per year. Trucks needed = total towing divided by one truck's capacity.","hints":"\"First: how many total tows does the whole fleet need in a year?\" \"Now: how many tows can one truck do in a year? What do you do with those two numbers?\" If they stall on how many Waymos there are, you can offer a rough number so they get to the division, which is where the real thinking is.","whyThisLevel":"Harder because it needs two separate estimates that you combine by dividing. You work out the total amount of towing needed, and separately how much one truck can handle, then divide one by the other. That \"divide the total by what one unit handles\" move is the new skill."},{"row":5,"title":"Landing in the right ballpark","question":"How many trees are on Earth: millions, billions, trillions, or hundreds of trillions?","answer":"About 3 trillion trees (the \"trillions\" bin). Most people guess far too low.","scoringGate":"Picking the right ballpark (trillions) with real reasoning behind it. A sound approach that lands one bin off can still win. Tie-breaker: correct bin AND reasoning.","path":"Land area, times the share that is forest, times trees per patch of forest. Land area is roughly knowable; the forest share and the trees-per-patch are wild guesses that carry most of the uncertainty.","hints":"\"Roughly how much of the Earth's land is covered in forest?\" \"About how many trees in a patch of forest the size of a city block? And how many blocks of forest are there?\" (very rough, just to get the multiplication going)","whyThisLevel":"Hard because almost every number in the chain is a guess, and the guesses multiply together, so small errors blow up fast. You cannot get a precise answer, the win is landing in the right ballpark. This is the row where you teach that \"right size\" is success, and being off by ten times is expected."},{"row":6,"title":"A normal calculation with a gut-defying answer","question":"A cloud holds about half a gram of water in every cubic meter of air. About how much weight does Storm move with a single, typical puffy cloud?","answer":"About 500 tons. This is roughly a million pounds, about the weight of a couple hundred cars. A puffy cloud is very roughly a cube one kilometer on each side, which is a billion cubic meters; a billion times half a gram is 500 million grams, about 500 tons.","scoringGate":"Realizing the cloud is huge, multiplying its size by the water-per-cubic-meter they were given, and being appropriately shocked. Judge the reasoning, not the exact cloud size, half or double the size is fine.","path":"Cloud size (roughly a cube a kilometer on a side, which is a billion cubic meters) times half a gram per cubic meter is about 500 tons.","hints":"\"How big is a puffy cloud, roughly? Guess its width, depth, and height.\" \"A cloud a kilometer on each side, how many cubic meters is that?\" (the answer, a billion, is where the jaw drops)","whyThisLevel":"The finale. It is a normal estimation chain, but the answer fights your gut, a cloud feels weightless, and it turns out to weigh as much as a couple hundred cars. The surprise comes from realizing how enormous a cloud actually is."}],"logic-paradox":[{"row":1,"title":"The quick gotcha","question":"You post a thirstrap on Instagram and get 100 likes. Some of them were bots. If the number of bot likes was 60 more than the number of real likes, how many real likes did you get?","answer":"20 real likes (and 80 bots). Check: 80 is 60 more than 20, and 80 + 20 = 100. The trap is that \"60 more\" makes the gut subtract 60 from 100 and say 40.","scoringGate":"The gate is landing on 20 with a correct account of why (the 60 is the difference, so you split what is left, not subtract 60 from 100).","path":"Resist the reflex (40) and test it: 40 real would need 100 bots to be \"60 more,\" totaling 140, too many. So set it up properly: real + (real + 60) = 100, meaning two times real = 40, so real = 20. Or intuitively: the 60 is the gap, so take it out (100 − 60 = 40) and split the rest evenly (20 each), then add the 60 back to one side (20 and 80).","hints":"\"Most people's first instinct is 40. Before you commit, check it: if there were 40 real likes, how many bots would that be, and does it add up to 100?\" \"The 60 is the difference between bots and real likes, not the number of bots. So how do you split the rest?\"","takeaway":"Almost everyone's gut says 40 first. That is exactly the point, and it is the shared experience, not a failure.","whyThisLevel":"The gentlest Logic move. Your gut hands you a confident wrong answer, but the fix is immediate once you slow down. No multi-step reasoning, no probability, just \"don't answer on reflex.\" The math is trivial; the whole challenge is that your brain grabs the wrong number. It sets the tone for the column: you are supposed to fall for these.","reskinNote":"This is the classic bat-and-ball problem, reskinned. The structure that must survive any further reskin: a round \"more than\" number sitting inside a total that is just above it, so the naive subtraction is tempting and the real answer is a surprising half of the small leftover."},{"row":2,"title":"The overlooked case","question":"Memo's shift at Badlands is from 10 PM to 3 AM. If during his shift the clocks fall back by 1 hour, for how many hours does Memo work?","answer":"6 hours. The clock only shows 5 (10 PM to 3 AM), but when it falls back, the hour between 1 and 2 AM happens twice, so Memo is there for 6 actual hours.","scoringGate":"The answer 6, with the recognition that falling back means an hour repeats, so he works longer than the clock suggests.","path":"Do the naive count (10 PM to 3 AM = 5 hours), then ask what \"falling back\" does. The clock rewinds, so the 1-to-2 hour is worked twice: 10-11, 11-12, 12-1, 1-2, 1-2 again, 2-3 = 6 hours. The joke and the lesson: falling back costs Memo an extra hour of work, not less.","hints":"\"When the clock falls back, does Memo get to leave earlier, or does he end up working an hour again?\" \"Trace it hour by hour: 10-11, 11-12, 12-1, 1-2, and then the clock jumps back to 1. Now what?\"","takeaway":"Both 5 (ignoring the change) and 4 (treating \"fall back\" as subtraction) are the expected traps.","whyThisLevel":"A step past Row 1. The gut answers thoroughly but incompletely: it does the clock arithmetic and either forgets the change or gets its direction backwards. \"Falling back\" sounds like losing an hour, so the instinct says he works less, when he actually works more, because the repeated hour has to be lived twice. The fix is not slowing down, it is tracing the shift hour by hour.","reskinNote":"An earlier draft ran 10 PM to 2 AM, which put the clock change exactly at the end of the shift, so the trap caught nobody and the answer was just 4. The change has to fall inside the window. Always run the trap and confirm it fires. Also note the wording deliberately supplies both the direction and the size of the change (\"fall back by 1 hour\") rather than requiring players to recall US DST rules, since recall is not reasoning."},{"row":3,"title":"The counting/probability trap","question":"Lyon wants to draw the Siren card from a deck of 10 tarot cards. He draws one card, looks at it, and shuffles it back in. He does this 10 times. What are the chances he will draw the Siren at least once?","answer":"About 65%. The chance he misses on any one draw is 9/10. Missing all ten in a row is 9/10 of 9/10 of 9/10, ten times over, which comes to about 35%. So he strikes out about a third of the time.","scoringGate":"Landing near two-thirds (anywhere around 60-70% with sound reasoning) and, crucially, explaining the flip: that you count the chance of never drawing it and subtract.Answering ~100% is the expected trap.","path":"The key move is counting the misses instead of the hits. Chance of missing one draw: 9/10. Missing all ten: 9/10 of 9/10 of 9/10... ≈ 35%. Since \"at least once\" and \"never\" are the only two options, at least once = 100% − 35% ≈ 65%.","hints":"\"Forget 10 draws. What if he draws twice? Chance of missing both is 9/10 of 9/10, about 80%, so he wins at least once about 20% of the time, not from adding but from counting the misses.\" \"'At least once' is messy to count directly (he could hit on draw 3, or 7, or both). But never is one clean story: miss, miss, miss, all ten times. Compute that.”","takeaway":"Probability is counting your slice of all possible worlds. **Multiply for \"and.\"** Each condition narrows what is left. Winning twice at 1-in-10 each is 1/10 of 1/10 = 1/100. \"Of\" means multiply in plain English (half *of* a half is a quarter). **Add for \"or,\" but only when the options cannot both happen.** Rolling a 1 or a 2 is 1/6 + 1/6, because you cannot roll both at once. The trap in this question is over-applying this: ten tries *can* overlap. **Flip when the question says \"at least one.\"** \"At least once\" is many messy scenarios; \"never\" is one clean story. Since they are the only two possibilities, compute the easy one and subtract: at least once = 100% − never.","whyThisLevel":"The first rung where you have to compute your way out of the trap. The gut says \"1-in-10 chance, 10 tries, that's a sure thing\" and it is badly wrong. The failure is not forgetting a case (Row 2), it is that intuition is terrible at judging how likely repeated chances actually are. Teams discuss here because arguing through why \"guaranteed\" is wrong is the work."},{"row":4,"title":"The conditional-probability flip","question":"Klinefelter Syndrome is a genetic condition in which a person is born with an extra X chromosome (XXY). It affects 1 in 1,000 people with a Y chromosome. The test for it is 99% accurate. In other words, it correctly identifies that someone does or does not have it 99% of the time. If a test comes back positive, what are the chances that someone with a Y chromosome actually has it?","answer":"About 9%. Imagine 1,000 people with a Y chromosome: About 1 actually has it, and the test catches it. That is 1 true positive. The other 999 do not have it, but the test is wrong 1% of the time, which is about 10 false positives. Total positive results: 1 + 10 = 11. Only 1 is real.","scoringGate":"Landing near 9% (anywhere around 5-15% with sound reasoning) and explaining why: that the false positives from the large healthy group swamp the single true positive.","path":"Of 1,000: ~1 has it (true positive), ~10 false alarms from the 999 who do not. That is 11 positives, 1 real, so about 1 in 11. The insight is that the test's accuracy is not the whole story; the base rate is.","hints":"\"Forget percentages. Imagine 1,000 people with a Y chromosome get tested. How many actually have it? Now, of the ones who don't, how many does the test get wrong?\" \"What if the condition affected 1 in 10 people instead? That would mean ~100 real cases against only ~9 false alarms.\"","takeaway":"Many people with Klinefelter are never diagnosed at all, and many who are only find out as adults, usually when they run into fertility problems. So the question is about false positives, and reality has the opposite problem too: a condition common enough to affect 1 in 1,000 mostly goes undetected. Testing statistics mislead in both directions.","whyThisLevel":"The hardest kind of gut-failure short of the finale. Row 3's error was misjudging a size. Here the error is refusing to believe that the rarity of the condition matters as much as the accuracy of the test. The gut hears \"99% accurate\" and answers \"99%,\" and it stays uncomfortable even after you prove otherwise. This is the row where teammates argue with each other, and then argue with the answer."},{"row":5,"title":"When the parts contradict the whole","question":"In 1973, two graduate departments at UC Berkeley had these admissions numbers: Department Men Women A 512 admitted of 825 (62%) 89 admitted of 108 (82%) F 22 admitted of 373 (6%) 24 admitted of 341 (7%) Across the two departments combined, who was admitted at a higher rate?","answer":"Men, about 45% compared to 25% for women. . Men: 512 + 22 = 534 admitted of 1,198 applied = ~45%. Women: 89 + 24 = 113 admitted of 449 applied = ~25%. Department A admits about 2 out of 3 applicants. Department F admits about 1 in 16. Roughly 69% of these men applied to the generous department; roughly 76% of these women applied to the brutal one. The combined number is not measuring how anyone was treated. It is measuring which line they stood in.","scoringGate":"Explaining that most men applied to the easy department and most women to the hard one, so the combined rate reflects where people applied rather than how they were treated. Exact percentages are not required; the reasoning is the gate. Answering \"women\" is the expected trap.","path":"Spot the lopsided distribution first, then either add each column and divide (534 of 1,198 versus 113 of 449) or reason it qualitatively: the men clustered where admission was generous, the women clustered where it was nearly impossible, so the combined number follows the departments.","hints":"\"Don't just compare the rates. Look at how many men applied to each department, and how many women.\" \"Department A lets in about two-thirds of everyone. Department F lets in about one in sixteen. If most men are in one and most women are in the other, what is the combined number actually telling you?\"","takeaway":"Berkeley was sued for sex discrimination in 1973: 44% of men admitted, 35% of women. Properly pooled, the data showed a small but statistically significant bias *in favor of* women. So why were women in the crowded departments? The paper's own answer: the easier departments were the ones requiring **more undergraduate math**, and women in 1973 were far less likely to have been given it. They were choosing the doors they were qualified for. The bias was real. It just happened years upstream in who got taught math.","whyThisLevel":"Row 4's gut error was refusing to accept that new information changes the odds. Here the gut is certain something is logically impossible: if women did better in every single department, they must do better overall. That feels like arithmetic itself. It is false, and it is provably false, which is what makes this a step up. The math is heavy because you cannot just compare rates, you have to weight them by how many people were actually in each group.","reskinNote":"Simpson's paradox breaks easily. What must survive any reskin: (1) two actors, two subgroups, one subgroup naturally easier; (2) actor A beats actor B in both subgroups; (3) lopsided distribution, where A does most of their work in the hard subgroup and B in the easy one (this is the engine); (4) a story reason for the lopsidedness; (5) equal or comparable totals, so the takeaway cannot be dismissed as \"one of them just did more.\" After any edit, re-check that A still wins both subgroups.","buildNote":"Render as a table (Department, Men, Women; rows A and F), figures preserved. No chart."},{"row":6,"title":"When the group can't want anything","question":"Three voters are ranking three candidates: a Democratic Socialist, a Democrat, and a Republican. Voter 1st 2nd 3rd Voter 1 Republican Democrat Democratic Socialist Voter 2 Democrat Democratic Socialist Republican Voter 3 Democratic Socialist Republican Democrat Each voter has a clear, consistent ranking. The group votes head-to-head, majority rules. Who wins?","answer":"There is no winner. Republican beats Democrat, 2-1 (Voters 1 and 3) Democrat beats Democratic Socialist, 2-1 (Voters 1 and 2) Democratic Socialist beats Republican, 2-1 (Voters 2 and 3) The majority prefers R to D, D to DS, and DS to R. It is a loop. Every one of those is a legitimate 2-1 majority.","scoringGate":"Recognizing there is no winner, and showing the cycle. The gate is whether they **checked the third matchup**. A team that checks R vs D, then D vs DS, and stops, concluding \"Republican, obviously,\" fell for it, and not from laziness: transitivity *promised* them the third check was unnecessary.","path":"Grind the three pairings by hand; it is counting to 2, three times. The difficulty is not the arithmetic, it is giving yourself permission to check a matchup that logic says is already settled.","hints":"\"Run all three head-to-heads. All of them. Even the one you think you already know.\" \"You've got R beating D, and D beating DS. So obviously R beats DS. Check it anyway.\"","takeaway":"It gets worse. Suppose they vote in rounds: two candidates first, the winner faces the third. Put **Democratic Socialist against the Democrat first**: the Democrat wins. Then the Democrat faces the Republican, and loses. **The Republican takes it.** Now run it again with a different pair going first, and a different candidate wins. Every candidate wins under some order. Nobody cheated, nobody voted dishonestly, every round was a clean majority, and **whoever scheduled the votes picked the winner.** Condorcet published this in 1785. In 1951, Kenneth Arrow generalized it: no voting system can satisfy a short list of obviously reasonable fairness conditions. He won a Nobel for it. This three-card puzzle grew into a proof that a perfect democracy cannot exist.","hostNote":"Someone may object that nobody really ranks Democratic Socialist first and Democrat last. That voter is *mathematically required*: if all three ranked along a single left-right axis, the cycle is impossible and the Democrat simply wins as the median. Cycles need someone ranking on a second dimension, like establishment versus outsider. That voter is real: 12% of Sanders 2016 primary voters voted Trump in the general, per the Cooperative Congressional Election Study (a survey of about 50,000 people).","whyThisLevel":"Row 5 told you a number meant something different than you thought. This one tells you the number does not exist. The gut is not just wrong, it is certain the result is impossible: if most prefer A to B, and most prefer B to C, then most prefer A to C. That is not a fact about voters, it feels like a law of thought. And it is false. Unlike every row before it, this one does not dissolve when you see the proof.","reskinNote":"The three rankings must be cyclic rotations of each other. Change any single voter's ranking and the paradox vanishes entirely. Three voters and three options is the tightest version; scaling up gains nothing and loses the ability to check it on your fingers. The three options must be plausibly rankable in any order.","buildNote":"Render as a table (Voter, 1st, 2nd, 3rd; three rows), exact rankings preserved — the cyclic order is load-bearing. No chart."}],"strategy":[{"row":1,"title":"Reading one person's incentive","question":"You want to go to an Ariana Grande concert in hopes of sitting next to your situationship, who is excited to go but will purchase mid-tier tickets because money is tight. If prices range from $100,000 to $1,000,000, what ticket price are you aiming for?","answer":"Around the middle of the range, roughly $500,000 to $550,000. The reasoning: they will buy a mid-tier seat, so to sit next to them you aim for the same mid-tier price zone. The exact number matters less than landing in the middle for the right reason.","scoringGate":"Aiming for the mid-range and explaining why (that is where the situationship will be, given their money constraint). Any figure in the mid-tier zone with sound reasoning is full credit.","path":"Their incentive (excited but money-tight) leads to a mid-tier ticket; to sit beside them, aim for the same mid-tier price; that is roughly the middle of the range.","hints":"\"What kind of ticket will your situationship actually buy, given their situation?\" \"If they are sitting in the mid-tier seats, where do you need to be to sit next to them?\"","whyThisLevel":"The gentlest strategic move. Figure out what one person will do from a single, obvious incentive, and act on it. No mutual reasoning yet (they are not thinking about what you will do). The math is light but real: their constraint (mid-tier, money is tight) maps to a price zone you reason toward."},{"row":2,"title":"Two incentives: align or clash","question":"Kevin the ranger pulls up to a barbershop where two vehicles are parked illegally: Lyon's black Camaro (a 4-seater) and a taco truck. Kevin gets a $15 bonus for every ticket he writes, plus an extra $5 for large vehicles. He only has time to ticket one before his shift ends. Is Lyon likely to get ticketed?","answer":"No, Lyon probably will not get ticketed. Kevin earns $20 for the taco truck ($15 plus the $5 large-vehicle bonus) versus $15 for the Camaro, so his incentive points him at the truck. Lyon is spared because a bigger target pulled Kevin away.","scoringGate":"Reading that Kevin's bonus is higher for the truck ($20 versus $15) and connecting that to Lyon's outcome (Kevin picks the truck, so Lyon is safe).","path":"Total each payoff: taco truck = $15 + $5 = $20; Camaro = $15. Kevin's incentive (maximize bonus) sends him to the truck, so Lyon's Camaro is left alone.","hints":"\"How much does Kevin earn for ticketing each vehicle?\" \"Which one is worth more to him, and what does that mean for the other car?\"","whyThisLevel":"One step up from Row 1. Instead of reading a single incentive, reason about how Kevin's incentive plays out across two options, and whether that works for or against Lyon. Still shallow (nobody is anticipating anyone's reaction), but now the answer depends on comparing two payoffs, which is a notch more math."},{"row":3,"title":"Anticipating one reaction","question":"Elyas has a 50%-off Panda Express coupon expiring today. Sheyla, the cashier, can accept or reject it, and she'll reject it if serving the order means cooking a fresh batch (she doesn't like extra work). There are exactly 3 scoops of orange chicken left in the tray and emptying the tray forces her to cook more. At regular price, each scoop is $5 (tax included). If Elyas has $10, how many scoops should he get?","answer":"2 scoops. Ordering 3 empties the tray, which forces Sheyla to cook more, so she rejects the coupon, and 3 scoops at full price ($15) is over his $10 budget. Ordering 2 leaves the tray non-empty, so Sheyla honors the coupon (2 scoops at $2.50 = $5). Reaching for the 3rd scoop is exactly what removes the discount.","scoringGate":"Landing on 2 and explaining the reaction chain: that ordering 3 triggers Sheyla's rejection, which backfires. Recognizing that the naive \"grab all 3\" is a trap is the sign they did the strategic work.","path":"Test the greedy move first: 3 scoops empties the tray, so Sheyla cooks a batch and rejects the coupon, so 3 scoops cost $15, unaffordable. Then test 2: tray not emptied, coupon honored, $5, affordable. The trap is that the coupon makes scoops look cheap enough to grab all 3, but grabbing the last one is what kills the coupon. Restraint wins.","hints":"\"What happens if Elyas tries to take all 3 scoops? How does Sheyla react?\" \"If she rejects the coupon, can he still afford 3? Work out both cases.\"","whyThisLevel":"The first genuinely strategic rung. Elyas's best move depends on how Sheyla will react to his order, one layer of \"if I do this, she'll do that.\" Reasoning through her reaction is the puzzle, which is why teams discuss it here. The math is a step up: compute across two price scenarios (coupon versus no coupon) and a supply limit."},{"row":4,"title":"Finding the stable point","question":"Froy and Ernesto are thrown in jail and interrogated separately. Each is offered the same deal. If you stay silent and so does the other, you each get 2 weeks. If you betray the other while they stay silent, you get just 1 week and they get 4. If you both betray each other, you each get 3 weeks. They can't communicate. If they act out of self-interest, what will each do?","answer":"Both betray, each getting 3 weeks. From either person's view, betraying beats staying silent no matter what the other does: if the other stays silent, betraying gets you 1 week instead of 2; if the other betrays, betraying gets you 3 instead of 4.","scoringGate":"Concluding both betray and showing why: that betraying is the better move for each person regardless of what the other picks. The reasoning (checking both cases) is the scoring gate.","path":"Reason from one person's side, checking both of the other's choices. For Froy: if Ernesto is silent, betray (1 versus 2 weeks); if Ernesto betrays, betray (3 versus 4). Betraying wins either way, and the same holds for Ernesto, so both betray and land at 3 weeks each. Stable because switching to silence alone only makes it worse.","hints":"\"Put yourself in Froy's shoes. If Ernesto stays silent, what is Froy's best move? Now, if Ernesto betrays, what is Froy's best move?\" \"If the same logic applies to both of them, where do they end up?\"","takeaway":"They would both be better off staying silent, 2 weeks each, but acting in self-interest cannot get them there. This is the classic Prisoner's Dilemma.","whyThisLevel":"Now both sides reason about each other at once, and the answer is where they settle: the pair of choices where neither would change his move given the other's. A step past Row 3's one-directional anticipation. The math carries the weight, since the specific sentences are what make betrayal the individually smart move."},{"row":5,"title":"Backward reasoning across rounds","question":"Bianca and Adore are splitting a $100,000 prize. They alternate making offers over at most 3 rounds, and the money shrinks each round they don't agree, per Drag Race rules: Round 1: $100,000 on the table. Bianca proposes a split. Adore accepts (done) or rejects. Round 2: If rejected, only $60,000 is left. Adore proposes a split. Bianca accepts or rejects. Round 3: If rejected again, only $20,000 is left. Bianca proposes a final split. Adore accepts, or rejects, and if she rejects, they both get $0. Both want as much money as possible. What should Bianca offer in Round 1?","answer":"Bianca offers Adore about $41,000 and keeps about $59,000, and Adore accepts immediately. Reasoned backward: Round 3 ($20,000, Bianca offers): if Adore rejects, she gets $0, so she accepts anything above $0. Bianca keeps almost all of it, Adore gets a token amount. Round 2 ($60,000, Adore offers): Adore knows Bianca would get about $20,000 by pushing to Round 3, so Adore offers Bianca just enough to beat that (about $20,000) and keeps about $40,000. Round 1 ($100,000, Bianca offers): Bianca knows Adore would get about $40,000 by pushing to Round 2, so Bianca offers Adore just over $40,000 (about $41,000) and keeps about $59,000. Adore accepts, since $41,000 now beats the $40,000 she would get by rejecting.","scoringGate":"Recognizing that you solve it backward (last round first) and landing on \"Bianca offers roughly $40,000 to $41,000 and keeps the rest, accepted in Round 1.\" The exact dollar is not required; the backward logic is the scoring gate. \"Split it 50/50\" or \"haggle all three rounds\" without the backward reasoning does not count.","path":"Work backward. Round 3: Adore takes anything over $0, so Bianca keeps nearly all of the $20,000. Round 2: Adore offers Bianca just more than that to avoid Round 3, keeping about $40,000. Round 1: Bianca offers Adore just more than that to avoid Round 2, keeping about $59,000, accepted on the spot. The counterintuitive result: it ends immediately, and moving first is an advantage.","hints":"\"Do not start at Round 1. Start at Round 3. If they get there, what happens, and who has the power?\" \"Once you know the Round 3 outcome, what would each person settle for in Round 2? Then work back to Round 1.\"","whyThisLevel":"The hardest strategic reasoning short of the finale. You cannot figure out the first offer without first working out the last round, then the middle, then the start, reasoning backward from the end. It stacks a sequence on top of Row 4's mutual reasoning. The math carries real weight: the shrinking pot is what determines every offer."},{"row":6,"title":"The counterintuitive result","question":"Imagine 8 people each secretly write down a number from 0 to 100. Whoever guesses closest to two-thirds of the average of all the guesses wins. What number should a smart player write, and why?","answer":"0 or ~22: 0 | Pure Logic: If everyone reasons perfectly, the number spirals down. Two-thirds of 50 is about 33, but everyone thinks that, so about 22, then about 15, down to 0, the only number no one would want to change. ~22 | Layered Realism: In a real group, not everyone reasons all the way down, so the average lands above 0 and the winning guess is usually about 20 to 25. Recognizing \"it spirals toward 0, but real people will not all reason that deep, so I aim a bit above 0\" models both the logic and the actual opponents, which is the sharpest play.","scoringGate":"Credit any answer that explains the downward spiral. **Tiebreak**: if both teams explain the spiral, the team that also layers in the realism (that real people will not all reason to 0, so the smart guess is about 22, not 0) wins.","path":"Start naive (average about 50, guess about 33), realize everyone reasons that too (about 22), and again (about 15), seeing it spiral toward 0. Pure-logic endpoint: 0. The great-not-just-good insight: real people will not all reach 0, so aim a bit above, about 22. The paradox: perfect reasoning says 0, but the winner is whoever best guessed how deep everyone else would actually reason.","hints":"\"If everyone guessed randomly, the average would be about 50, so what is two-thirds of that? Now, will everyone else think the same thing?\" \"Each time you assume everyone reasons one step further, where does the number go? Does it ever stop? And in a real room, does everyone actually reason that far?\"","whyThisLevel":"The finale, and the deepest strategic reasoning in the column. Not \"what is the clever move\" but \"how many layers deep does everyone reason, knowing everyone else is reasoning too?\" Each layer of \"but they'll think that, so I should\" pushes the answer downward with no bottom. The surprise: flawless reasoning points everyone toward 0, yet 0 almost never wins, because real people do not all reason that far. It is the deepest expression of the whole column's skill: reasoning about other minds reasoning about you."}],"data-literacy":[{"row":1,"title":"The visible distortion","question":"Shadi is trying to sell you one of two cars. He shows you this and says: *'Both run at 800 RPM on average while parked, identical engines, both perfectly healthy.'* [See Build Note for chart specs] What's Shadi not telling you?","answer":"The engines are not identical. Car A's speed is steady (a healthy engine). Car B's swings violently, which is what a failing engine does when cylinders misfire. The average hides the variation. Car B is dying, and Shadi quoted a true number that conceals it.","scoringGate":"Recognizing that the average conceals the difference, and identifying that Car B's readings swing wildly while Car A's are stable, so B is the unhealthy one. Saying \"they're not identical\" alone does not clear the gate; the diagnosis, that the average hides the spread, is the gate.","path":"Ignore the average and read the two rows. Car A barely moves; Car B is all over the place. An engine that cannot hold a steady speed while parked is misfiring or failing, so despite the matching average, B is in trouble.","hints":"\"Shadi gave you the average. Look at the actual numbers behind it. Do the two cars look the same second to second?\" \"Car A stays near 800 the whole time. What is Car B doing? What would make an engine's speed jump around like that?\"","takeaway":"A healthy engine runs almost flat while parked, wobbling only about 50 to 100 RPM. A failing one surges and dips as cylinders misfire. Shadi's single number was incomplete and concealed what you would want to know before buying. This is the most common data trick there is: quote a mean, hide the range.","whyThisLevel":"The gentlest interrogation move. The claim is technically true (both really do average 800) and rhetorically false (the cars are nothing alike). Everything you need is on the page, both the averages and the actual readings, so catching it is looking past the summary to the numbers underneath. No hidden data. The flaw is visible the moment you read the chart instead of the sentence.","buildNote":"Car A, engine speed (RPM) while parked, over 10 seconds: 790, 810, 795, 805, 800, 800, 810, 790 *(average: 800)* Car B, engine speed (RPM) while parked, over 10 seconds: 500, 1150, 600, 1050, 450, 1200, 400, 1050 *(average: 800).* Two line charts sharing one identical y-axis (critical — independent scaling kills the contrast). Dashed line at 800 on both. Car A flat, Car B a zigzag. Chart is honest, so no corrected version."},{"row":2,"title":"The misleading comparison","question":"Café de Casa, a Brazilian chain, has two locations in San Francisco. The Fisherman's Wharf location seats a maximum of 80 people; the Castro location seats a maximum of 50. In one day, Fisherman's Wharf serves 512 people and Castro serves 400. The Castro manager claims his location serves more diners per seat than Fisherman's Wharf, and that he therefore deserves a raise. Assuming both locations have the same hours and diners spend about the same time eating, is he correct?","answer":"Yes, he is correct. Per seat, Fisherman's Wharf serves 512 divided by 80 = 6.4 diners, while Castro serves 400 divided by 50 = 8 diners. Castro turns over more customers per seat, so relative to its size it satisfies more demand.","scoringGate":"Recognizing that raw counts are not a fair comparison because the locations differ in size, and dividing by seats to get the per-seat rate (6.4 vs 8). The diagnosis, that you must adjust for capacity, is the gate.","path":"Notice the locations are different sizes, so raw totals are not comparable. Divide each by its seats: 512 / 80 = 6.4, 400 / 50 = 8. Castro's higher per-seat number means the manager is right, even though his total looks smaller.","hints":"\"Fisherman's Wharf serves more people total. But it's also bigger. Is 'total served' a fair way to compare two differently sized places?\" \"Put each location's customers next to its seats. How many diners per seat does each one handle?\"","takeaway":"2 true numbers can point the wrong way if they are not put on equal footing.","whyThisLevel":"A step past Row 1. Nothing here visually screams; all four numbers look reasonable, and the raw totals (512 beats 400) make it look like Fisherman's Wharf is the busier location. The move is to ask whether the two locations are compared fairly, given they are different sizes. Everything you need is on the page; you just have to relate the counts to the seats instead of taking totals at face value.","otherNotes":"Unlike most Data Literacy questions, the claimant here is *correct*. The trap is the player's own too-quick reading (totals favor Fisherman's Wharf), and scrutiny *vindicates* the claim. This teaches that interrogating a claim does not always mean debunking it; sometimes it confirms it, and the thing to get past is the naive headline number."},{"row":3,"title":"The missing denominator","question":"You're at Safeway and your favorite yogurt, Yoplait, has a new label: *'1,000 people prefer us over Chobani.'* Using math, prove why this is misleading.","answer":"The label is meaningless without context that is missing: No denominator. If 1,200 were asked and 1,000 preferred Yoplait, that is ~83%, a real result. If 100,000 were asked and only 1,000 preferred Yoplait, that is 1%, meaning ~99% actually preferred Chobani, and the label hides a landslide *against* Yoplait. No opposing count. The label never says how many preferred Chobani, so \"1,000 prefer us\" is compatible with millions preferring the competitor.","scoringGate":"Identifying at least one of the two missing pieces (the total surveyed, or the count preferring Chobani) and, for the denominator, ideally showing *why* it matters by demonstrating that the same 1,000 supports opposite conclusions depending on the total.","path":"Notice the label gives a count with no total. Then test what the total could be: 1,000 out of 1,200 is impressive; 1,000 out of 100,000 is a disaster for Yoplait. Since the same number supports opposite conclusions, the claim is empty without the denominator.","hints":"\"1,000 people prefer Yoplait, out of how many who tried both? Does the label tell you?\" \"Imagine they asked 1,200 people. Now imagine they asked 100,000. Does '1,000 preferred us' mean the same thing in both cases?\"","takeaway":"This is one of the most common tricks in advertising and headlines: quote an impressive-sounding raw number and omit what it is a fraction of. The missing denominator is the single most useful thing to look for in any statistic. Also, to be able to compare to competitors, the data on competitors must be available.","whyThisLevel":"The first rung where the flaw is not on the page, it is a hole in the page. Nothing about \"1,000 people\" is false, and it sounds like a lot. But to know whether it means anything, you need a number they did not give you: out of how many people asked? That is the step up from Row 2, where the correcting number was printed. Here you have to notice it is missing, which you cannot do by reading harder. The prompt deliberately says \"prove,\" echoing the discipline of the whole game: it is not enough to assert a claim is misleading; you have to show it. At this rung it is fine to tell players there is a gap; finding what it is is still the work."},{"row":4,"title":"The misleading axis","question":"Your friend claims that Damascus has about 2 to 3 times as many people as the other Levantine capitals. He shows you a chart to settle it. [See Build Note for chart specs] Is he right?","answer":"No. The numbers are close: Amman ~2.27M, Beirut ~2.40M, Damascus ~2.69M. Damascus has only about 1.18 times as many people as Amman, not 2 to 3 times. The chart fakes the gap by starting the y-axis at 2,250,000 instead of 0. Drawn from a zero baseline, all three bars are tall and nearly equal.","scoringGate":"Recognizing the y-axis does not start at zero and that this manufactures the gap, plus checking the actual ratio (~1.18x, nowhere near 2 to 3x). Answering \"yes\" is the trap.","path":"The tell is Amman: its bar is nearly invisible, yet it represents 2.27 million people. That mismatch signals a chopped axis. Check the floor (2,250,000), then test the ratio: 2,685,000 / 2,273,000 ≈ 1.18, so Damascus is about 18% bigger, not 2 to 3x.","hints":"\"Where does the vertical axis start? What happens to the bars if it doesn't start at zero?\" \"Do the math on his actual claim: divide Damascus's number by Amman's. Is it really 2 to 3 times?\"","takeaway":"The truncated y-axis is the single most common chart trick in real media, precisely because it is invisible unless you look for it. It is not always dishonest (sometimes you legitimately want to zoom in), but it becomes a lie the moment it implies a huge gap where the real difference is minor. Footnote: these are real metro-area figures (2024 to 2025) but approximate, and Damascus's is especially uncertain because of wartime displacement, a small lesson in itself about trusting precise-looking numbers.","hostNote":"The chart deliberately omits Jerusalem because its population has no single apolitical figure – it depends on contested choices (which municipal boundaries, whether East Jerusalem's residents are counted as part of an Israeli city), so the number itself encodes a political position. If it comes up, use it: a guest catching the omission is the skill working in real time.","whyThisLevel":"The chart looks clean and persuasive, no visible contradiction like Row 1 had. The move is to notice what the chart is not showing: the y-axis does not start at zero. Starting it at 2,250,000 chops off almost the entire height of every bar and turns a small difference into an apparent landslide. That is an absence to catch, not a distortion you can see, which is what makes it Act 2. And the claim is now specific (\"2 to 3 times\"), so you have to check the ratio against the labels to debunk it.","buildNote":"Same three bars on both charts. Chart, 'Population of Levantine Capitals': three bars, y-axis running from 2,250,000 to 2,700,000. Bars labeled: Amman, Jordan, 2,273,000; Beirut, Lebanon, 2,402,000; Damascus, Syria, 2,685,000. Damascus's bar towers over the others; Amman's is a thin sliver. Question side: y-axis floor 2,250,000 (this truncation is the deception — do not start at zero). Answer side: floor 0, bars now near-equal. Both required."},{"row":5,"title":"Correlation is not causation","question":"In 2011, the NYPD detained, questioned, and conducted pat-downs on 685,724 people, invoking the stop-and-frisk practice allowed under reasonable suspicion. That same year, New York City's violent crime rate was at lows the city hadn't seen in decades. The city's then-mayor, Michael Bloomberg, made the case that aggressive stop-and-frisk was taking guns off the street and driving crime down, and that pulling back on it would put the city in danger. The stops were high and crime was low. What additional information, if any, do you need to prove stop-and-frisk caused the drop?","answer":"Two things moving together does not establish that one caused the other. What you would need is some way to see what crime would have done *without* the stops: A comparison group. A U.S. city without stop-and-frisk and the rates of crime over the same period of time. A removal test. Crime rates after the removal of the stop-and-frisk policy","scoringGate":"The gate is recognizing that high-stops-plus-low-crime cannot prove causation and naming what would be needed to test it: (1) a comparison group (crime where there was no such policy) or a removal test (what happened when stops ended). \"Correlation isn't causation\" as a bare slogan does not clear it; a specific test or alternative explanation does. Answering \"no additional information needed, the correlation proves it\" is the trap.","path":"Separate the two facts (stops high, crime low) from the claimed link between them, then ask what would let you see the counterfactual. A bigger trend affecting everyone or a test of removing the supposed cause each shows the causal story does not hold.","hints":"\"To prove the stops caused it, you'd want to compare against a world without the stops. Where could you find something like that, another city, or a later time when the stops ended?\" \"If crime fell just as much in places that never used stop-and-frisk, or kept falling after New York abandoned it, would his claim still stand?\"","takeaway":"When someone says A caused B because they happened together, ask what else was going on, and ask what happened when A went away. **Comparison group.** Crime was falling across the entire US, including in cities without stop-and-frisk, where crime fell just as much. **A removal test.** After a 2013 court ruling found the program unconstitutional, stops collapsed, but crime didn’t surge; it kept falling. **Racial bias.** In 2011, about 84% of those stopped were Black or Latino. Years later, with a fraction of the stops, the share of stopped people who were Black actually rose (59% of stops against a 24% population in 2022). Whether the program was large or small, it fell on the same people.","hostNote":"The defensible claim is that the correlation does not establish causation, and the fuller data (national decline, plus crime continuing to fall after stops ended) shows the causal story is unsupported. Avoid overstating it as \"proven to do nothing,\" a stronger claim than the data licenses; the game's own credibility depends on not overclaiming. The point is the reasoning error, not a verdict on every effect of the policy. The lesson is transferable, the same co-movement-is-not-causation error drives bad claims about diets, economics, and advertising, which is useful to name if the room's energy gets political.","whyThisLevel":"The step from Act 2 into inference. Nothing here is hidden or distorted; the numbers are real and fairly stated. What is on trial is the conclusion: two things moved together, and the claim is that one caused the other. You cannot catch this by finding a missing number or a chopped axis. You have to interrogate the leap from \"these happened at the same time\" to \"this caused that,\" and identify what would actually test it. That is the hardest data-literacy move, which is why it anchors Act 3."},{"row":6,"title":"The manufactured finding","question":"Egypt is convinced that playing the right song on his website will make more people buy what he sells. To find out, he tests 20 different songs, one at a time. For each song, he shows the site to about 100 visitors with the song and 100 without, and checks whether the song produced significantly more purchases. Differences are statistically significant if there's less than a 5% chance of seeing them by luck alone. 19 of the songs show nothing. But one, a track by Kali Uchis, comes back significant: noticeably more purchases, clearing the 5% bar. Egypt posts on Instagram: *'Kali Uchis boosts my sales.'* His calculations are all correct. So why should you distrust his post?","answer":"The Kali Uchis result is almost certainly a fluke, manufactured by testing 20 songs and reporting the one that hit. The 5% threshold means each song has a 5% chance of looking significant by luck. Test one song and a false alarm is unlikely. Test 20 and you expect about one false alarm on average (20 times 5% = 1).","scoringGate":"Identifying that testing many songs and reporting only the winner manufactures the false positive, that the Kali Uchis result is expected noise from running 20 tests, not a real finding. **Tie-breaker:** when both teams clear the gate, the team that *shows the math* (20 tests times 5% ≈ 1 expected false positive by chance) wins over a team that reasons it only qualitatively.","path":"Look at the design. The 5% threshold means a 1-in-20 chance of a false positive per test, even when nothing real is going on. Egypt ran 20 tests, so about one false positive was essentially guaranteed.","hints":"\"Forget Kali Uchis for a second. How many songs did Egypt test in total? If every song were completely useless, how many would you still expect to look 'significant' just by chance?\" \"The threshold allows a 5% chance of a false alarm per song. He tested 20 songs. 20 times 5% is what?\"","takeaway":"This is called p-hacking, or the multiple-comparisons problem, and it is one of the biggest reasons published science, especially in nutrition and health, keeps reversing itself. Coffee causes cancer; coffee prevents cancer; eggs are bad; eggs are fine. Many of these are single significant findings pulled from studies that quietly tested dozens of things. The defense is the same question the game has been teaching: not *is this fact true?* but *how did they find it, and what aren't they showing me?*","whyThisLevel":"The finale, and the one question where fact-checking fails completely. Every prior question had a flaw you could point to: a hidden number, a chopped axis, a bad causal leap. Here, nothing is false. The data is real, the statistics are done correctly, the Kali Uchis result genuinely clears the bar. You can only catch it by asking how the finding was found, the deepest data-literacy move there is, and the reason bad science and bad marketing slip past even careful readers.","otherNotes":"The subject is Egypt, the game's own designer, caught p-hacking his own website. That is deliberate. The whole game argues that anyone can fool themselves with numbers, including the person who built a game about not being fooled by numbers, which is the same humility the project's process documentation is built around."}]}};
